dc:title: Ecological theory and endangered species
dc:creator: Kareiva P.
dc:description: Schemske et al. have reviewed 98 different recovery plans for endangered plants. Most recovery plans neglect or arm-wave their way through population processes as fundamental as the species' capacity for growth under ideal conditions. Mangel and Tier then address the importance of catastrophes for species' persistence, using a simple and powerful new mathematical approach. Even if catastrophes do not, over the short term, appear to drive a population's fate, they can be so important that we need to rethink our views on everything from standard viability analyses to the merits of fragmented habitat reserves. Doak and Mills assess the role of favored ecological platitudes in debates about endangered species. Many of the conceptual centerpieces of conservation biology can lead us astray when confronting a real world of scanty data and complex habitat relationships and they recommend different approaches that are needed to address these real world shortcomings. -from Editor
